<h1 class="ds-page-title">Accessibility</h1>
<p class="ds-page-lead">
    Guidelines for creating accessible interfaces in COMPASS. These guidelines ensure that all users, regardless of ability, can access and use COMPASS effectively.
</p>

<h2>Colour contrast</h2>
<p>
    Sufficient colour contrast ensures that text is readable for users with visual impairments or in various lighting conditions.
</p>

<h3>Contrast requirements</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Normal text:</strong> Minimum contrast ratio of 4.5:1 against background</li>
    <li><strong>Large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold):</strong> Minimum contrast ratio of 3:1 against background</li>
    <li><strong>Interactive elements:</strong> Minimum contrast ratio of 3:1 against background</li>
    <li><strong>Non-text elements (icons, borders):</strong> Minimum contrast ratio of 3:1</li>
</ul>

<h3>Testing contrast</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Good contrast</div>
    <div style="background: #005ea5; color: white; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 4px; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        <strong>Good contrast:</strong> White text on blue background (meets WCAG AA)
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f4f8fb; color: #0b0c0c; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid #e1e4e8;">
        <strong>Good contrast:</strong> Dark text on light background (meets WCAG AA)
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Colour contrast guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Never rely on colour alone to convey information</li>
    <li>Use tools like WebAIM Contrast Checker to verify contrast ratios</li>
    <li>Test with different background colours and themes</li>
    <li>Ensure sufficient contrast in both light and dark modes</li>
    <li>Consider users with colour blindness when choosing colour combinations</li>
</ul>

<h2>Screen readers</h2>
<p>
    Screen readers convert text and interface elements into speech or braille output for users with visual impairments.
</p>

<h3>Semantic HTML</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Semantic structure</div>
    <pre><code>&lt;header&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Page title&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/header&gt;
&lt;nav aria-label="Main navigation"&gt;
    &lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Link&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;main&gt;
    &lt;section&gt;
        &lt;h2&gt;Section title&lt;/h2&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Content&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/main&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Footer content&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/footer&gt;</code></pre>
</div>

<h3>ARIA labels and roles</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - ARIA attributes</div>
    <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" aria-label="Close dialog">
        <i class="fas fa-times" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    </button>
    <div role="alert" aria-live="polite">
        Status message appears here
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Screen reader guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Use semantic HTML elements (header, nav, main, section, article, footer)</li>
    <li>Provide descriptive labels for all interactive elements</li>
    <li>Use ARIA labels when text labels are not visible</li>
    <li>Mark decorative images with <code>aria-hidden="true"</code></li>
    <li>Provide alternative text for informative images</li>
    <li>Use heading hierarchy correctly (h1, h2, h3, etc.)</li>
    <li>Ensure form inputs have associated labels</li>
    <li>Provide skip links for keyboard navigation</li>
    <li>Test with screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Keyboard users</h2>
<p>
    All functionality should be accessible via keyboard navigation for users who cannot or prefer not to use a mouse.
</p>

<h3>Keyboard navigation</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Keyboard accessible buttons</div>
    <div class="btn-group" role="group" aria-label="Action buttons">
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" tabindex="0">Primary action</button>
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-secondary" tabindex="0">Secondary action</button>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Focus indicators</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Visible focus</div>
    <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" style="outline: 2px solid #005ea5; outline-offset: 2px;">
        Button with visible focus indicator
    </button>
</div>

<h3>Keyboard navigation guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible</li>
    <li>Provide visible focus indicators for all focusable elements</li>
    <li>Maintain logical tab order throughout the page</li>
    <li>Support standard keyboard shortcuts (Enter, Space, Escape, Arrow keys)</li>
    <li>Avoid keyboard traps (situations where users cannot navigate away)</li>
    <li>Provide skip links to bypass repetitive navigation</li>
    <li>Ensure modals and dialogs can be closed with Escape key</li>
    <li>Test navigation using only keyboard (Tab, Shift+Tab, Enter, Space, Arrow keys)</li>
    <li>Ensure focus management in dynamic content (modals, dropdowns)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Zoom</h2>
<p>
    Users should be able to zoom in up to 200% without losing functionality or content.
</p>

<h3>Responsive design</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Responsive viewport</div>
    <pre><code>&lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1"&gt;</code></pre>
</div>

<h3>Zoom guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Use relative units (rem, em, %) instead of fixed pixels for text sizes</li>
    <li>Ensure content reflows properly when zoomed</li>
    <li>Avoid horizontal scrolling at 200% zoom</li>
    <li>Test pages at different zoom levels (100%, 150%, 200%)</li>
    <li>Ensure interactive elements remain usable when zoomed</li>
    <li>Use flexible layouts that adapt to different screen sizes</li>
    <li>Ensure text remains readable at all zoom levels</li>
</ul>

<h2>Reflow</h2>
<p>
    Content should reflow to fit different screen sizes and orientations without requiring horizontal scrolling.
</p>

<h3>Flexible layouts</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Responsive grid</div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12 mb-3">
            <div class="card">
                <div class="dfe-adminui-card__body">Column 1 - Adapts to screen size</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12 mb-3">
            <div class="card">
                <div class="dfe-adminui-card__body">Column 2 - Adapts to screen size</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Reflow guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Use responsive design principles (mobile-first approach)</li>
    <li>Avoid fixed widths that cause horizontal scrolling</li>
    <li>Use flexible grid systems (Bootstrap columns)</li>
    <li>Ensure content stacks vertically on small screens</li>
    <li>Test on different screen sizes (mobile, tablet, desktop)</li>
    <li>Test in both portrait and landscape orientations</li>
    <li>Ensure tables can scroll horizontally or be reformatted on small screens</li>
    <li>Use CSS media queries to adapt layouts</li>
</ul>

<h2>Voice control</h2>
<p>
    Voice control users navigate and interact with interfaces using voice commands.
</p>

<h3>Voice control considerations</h3>
<div class="component-example">
    <div class="component-example-title">Example - Voice-friendly labels</div>
    <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" id="saveButton">
        Save changes
    </button>
    <button type="button" class="btn btn-secondary" id="cancelButton">
        Cancel
    </button>
</div>

<h3>Voice control guidelines</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Use descriptive, unique labels for all interactive elements</li>
    <li>Avoid generic labels like "Click here" or "Button"</li>
    <li>Ensure buttons and links have clear, action-oriented text</li>
    <li>Provide visible labels that match voice command expectations</li>
    <li>Use consistent naming conventions across the application</li>
    <li>Ensure form inputs have clear, associated labels</li>
    <li>Test with voice control software (Dragon, Voice Control on macOS/iOS)</li>
    <li>Avoid elements that are only identifiable by visual position</li>
</ul>

<h2>Accessibility checklist</h2>
<p>
    Use this checklist when creating or reviewing COMPASS features:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>✓ All text meets minimum colour contrast requirements</li>
    <li>✓ All images have appropriate alt text</li>
    <li>✓ All form inputs have associated labels</li>
    <li>✓ All interactive elements are keyboard accessible</li>
    <li>✓ Focus indicators are visible on all focusable elements</li>
    <li>✓ Page structure uses semantic HTML</li>
    <li>✓ Heading hierarchy is logical and sequential</li>
    <li>✓ ARIA labels are used where appropriate</li>
    <li>✓ Content is readable and functional at 200% zoom</li>
    <li>✓ Layout reflows properly on different screen sizes</li>
    <li>✓ No keyboard traps exist</li>
    <li>✓ Skip links are provided for main content</li>
    <li>✓ Error messages are clear and accessible</li>
    <li>✓ Dynamic content updates are announced to screen readers</li>
</li>
</ul>

<h2>Testing accessibility</h2>
<p>
    Regular testing ensures COMPASS remains accessible to all users:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Automated testing:</strong> Use tools like axe DevTools, WAVE, or Lighthouse</li>
    <li><strong>Manual testing:</strong> Test with keyboard navigation only</li>
    <li><strong>Screen reader testing:</strong> Test with NVDA (Windows), JAWS (Windows), or VoiceOver (macOS/iOS)</li>
    <li><strong>Zoom testing:</strong> Test at 200% zoom level</li>
    <li><strong>Responsive testing:</strong> Test on various screen sizes and orientations</li>
    <li><strong>User testing:</strong> Include users with disabilities in testing when possible</li>
</ul>

